text.tspan: GPU Accelerated Calculation of Radio Viewsheds

flowRoot.flowPara: Radio viewsheds are, in simple terms, the area of ground that a radio emitter (such as a cell mast) can see. Radio viewshed simulations are useful in helping to plan the placements of these emitters, and are used by telecoms companies, rural ISPs, network researchers, and other indivudals interested in what can be seen from where.

Geoinformatics applications used to generate viewsheds typically rely on the CPU to do their calculations. Because maps of the Earth tend to be implemented as grids of heights, and each cell is independent of the other, GPUs are well suited to calculating viewsheds.

GPUs are designed to operate as grids of slow, simple compute units operating together. As such, GPUs are able to test for visibility of many dozens of cells at once, outstripping the speedier CPUs on account of the massive parallelism they can bring to certain problems.

The implementations were then tested against each other for speedup. The performance of the implementations is highly variable dependent on the content of the heightmaps, so the same maps with known performance characteristics were used.

The times were compared and speedups were calculated. Across the test dataset we can see speedups ranging from TODO to TODO, with example real world data (based of heightmaps of Edinburgh sourced from EDINA) showing speedups of ~241x (6h34m to 1m38s).
GPU acceleration did have higher overheads to start calculations, meaning that only datasets over a certain size are faster (approximately 1024x1024).
Overall, GPU accelaration has proved to be viable and the speed improvements significant.
The implementation was carried out targeting a test machine with the following configuration:
Dual NVIDIA Tesla K40c compute GPUs
The software was implemented in C, using OpenCL to write the ray tracing kernel used to test for cell visibility.
Two implementations were completed, one running exclusively on the CPU, and one using the GPU to accelerate calculations.

Both implementations were based on Bresenham's Line Drawing Algorithm to trace from the emitter location to the cell under test, with modifications to allow testing the height of the ray compared to the terrain as it passes over each cell. There were also some minor modifications to suit the differences between the CPU and GPU platforms.
